[normal]B
[normal]enches.
[normal] Of 
[normal]course you know Dominique Gracia
[normal],
[normal] who has organised all of this.
[normal]We started this inquiry taking witness statements from October last year, although it seems a long time ago. We are doing it on the basis of our remit as a 
[normal]S
[normal]ub
[normal]-C
[normal]ommittee of the European Union Select Committee in the House of Lords to scrutinise
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]W
[normal]e have three specific areas: the internal market, infrastructure and employment. We have done various reports since this Parliament began. We have a five-year Parliament span and we are just towards the end of the fourth year. We have done things like women on boards, innovation and research and the Channel Tunnel. So you can see the disparate types of work we do.
[normal]We decided to look at youth unemployment because without doubt it is probably the most serious problem facing the European Union. There are some countries that are managing to sort it out.
[normal]We have taken evidence from all sorts of people. We have taken statements from 
[normal]young people
[normal] themselves, which was a really good thing that we did. 
[normal]W
[normal]e had two very interesting sessions: one in Birmingham and one in Liverpool. We found just how 
[normal]difficult
[normal] it is out there, with the interaction of social problems
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]T
[normal]he real problem is that
[normal], 
[normal]while some people can be unemployed and then pick themselves up and get into the labour market, and then have careers and go steaming on
[normal], 
[normal]some of these people are without hope. I do not think they can see it on their radar screen. Then there are the implications of that not only for the people themselves, who are going to have a much worse life than other people born at the same time as them in different circumstances, but there are the social implications
[normal]—
[normal]riots and all sort of things. We have seen very little of it in the United Kingdom
[normal]—it does not happen every weekend—but 
[normal]it is destabilising and very upsetting for those who have tried to do something about it. 
[normal]T
[normal]hat is one of the major problems.
[normal]We also took evidence from business on the day-to-day operations of things like apprenticeships and that was very helpful. 
[normal]T
[normal]here are definitely some areas we can look at that are going to help us throughout.
[normal] 
[normal]Now we have decided that, as it was the European Union, we had better come here. It is the first time our Committee ha
[normal]s 
[normal]taken evidence 
[normal]in 
[normal]Brussels
[normal] in this Parliament, so 
[normal]we are very grateful to you. We have a series of questions that you have been given in advance.
[normal] M
[normal]y first question is: to what extent do you see the issue as being about the demand side
[normal]—
[normal]the availability of jobs
[normal]—
[normal]and to what extent is 
[normal]it 
[normal]the supply side: how well young people are prepared for the labour market, in terms of skills and education, the point really being their employability?
[normal]Max Uebe[bold]: First, let me thank you for coming over and for your interest. We very much look forward to your final report. It is when?
[normal]The Chairman:[bold] April 2014, just a couple of months.
[normal]Max Uebe[bold]: So a couple of months to go. When I started in the Cabinet with Commissioner Andor’s predecessor, Commissioner 
[normal]Š
[normal]pid
[normal]l
[normal]a, there was a report by the House of Lords on labour law. It was early days for me and I was not involved very much but I remember the high quality of the report, which was very much appreciated. Our relations with the 
[normal]UK
[normal] are not always the easiest, so also in this context we look forward to the report based on the sound evidence that you have collected, which perhaps can also help the debate from our point of view. 
[normal]The Chairman:[bold] 
[normal]Thank you for that comment. That is very important. Thank you.
[normal]Max Uebe:[bold] On your question on demand and supply
[normal], we 
[normal]try to address it from both angles. There is clearly both a demand side and a supply side problem in most member states. Of course it is dangerous to generalise because the situation across the European Union is very diverse. It is no secret. If you look at the map, at the Mediterranean countries, in 
[normal]Greece
[normal] and 
[normal]Spain
[normal] youth unemployment is up to almost 60%, whereas in the centre it 
[normal]is 
[normal]4% or 5%. In general, we try to address the fact that young people without the right skills will never have a chance. You mention young people who are caught in this cycle of unemployment over generations. They will not have the opportunity to enter the labour market to find sustainable labour market attachment. Obviously, on the other side, what we always say is that, whatever we do here in terms of apprenticeship reform, the Youth Guarantee and so on, it will not work if the economy as a whole is not picking up. We are not naive. Without that it will not be possible. But our objective is to at least have young people ready and prepared for jobs that hopefully will come up soon
[normal],
[normal] because there is some light now at the end of the tunnel. Recovery is coming. The big question is: will it be a jobless recovery or will there be new jobs? I would argue that it is both. It is very important.
[normal]If you look at the Youth Guarantee—and I assume you have looked at the recommendation behind the Youth Guarantee—this is our flagship in the unit. This is our umbrella for all the policy measures we take in the fight against youth u
[normal]nemployment. It can be argued that 
[normal]there 
[normal]you have both in a way. There is a recommendation to reinforce youth entrepreneurship. You can use money from the 
[normal]youth employment initiative
[normal]—this €6 billion package—to finance recruitment or wage subsidies, and a large part of course is upskilling and so on. We try to tackle both
[normal],
[normal] the Commissioner will argue. 
[normal]Perhaps I should say here, in brackets, that it 
[normal]is not usual for me to speak to you before you speak to the Commissioner. It is not the most normal or pleasant
[normal] way. It is a bit tricky.
[normal]The Chairman:[bold] For you?
[normal]Max [bold]Uebe[bold]: Yes, of course, because I do not 
[normal]want
[normal] you to say later on, “But Max said so and so”
[normal].
[normal]The Chairman:[bold] We will not.
[normal]Max Uebe[bold]: I also like to keep questions more on a technical level. For example, this is a question that the Commissioner would love to address. He is an economist and he thinks a lot about these macroeconomic questions as well.
[normal]The Chairman:[bold] Thank you. Does anyone want to comment on any points that Mr Uebe has mentioned? The thing that struck me is what you said about this total commitment to the flagship policy, which is the Youth Guarantee.
[normal]Q180 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal] 
[normal]Lord Brooke of Alverthorpe:[bold] On the second question, I would like to tease you out a little on the Commission’s programme for developing standards for training and apprenticeship quality. As you know, there is quite a focus in the 
[normal]UK
[normal] on returning to what we had 20 or 30 years ago, which were quality apprenticeships. We are now trying to very substantially increase the number of young people undergoing apprenticeships. Could you explain a little bit more
[normal] what you believe that centrally
[normal]—without any question there is a role for you—
[normal]you can contribute
[normal], because there is such a diverse application of apprenticeships between one nation and another? Are you hoping to achieve minimum standards or a minimum quality? Do you think it is possible or preferable to give a general exhortation that people should be moving in this direction but leave it to them to develop the systems as they see appropriate to their own circumstances? 
[normal]Max Uebe:[bold] First, we have to clearly distinguish between traineeships and apprenticeships. Those are dealt with here in the unit by two different people. 
[normal]I should say, in brackets, to give you an idea that we 
[normal]are the policy unit working on youth unemployment. You mentioned that 
[normal]this 
[normal]is one of the biggest problems in the European Union
[normal],
[normal] but we have 3.5 people working on that. 
[normal]I say that t
[normal]o give you an idea. We have staff cuts and I just managed to get one additional post. But, given the magnitude of the problem, it is always interesting to see the reaction of people 
[normal]when 
[normal]I give this information. It is quite something. We have one colleague working on traineeships. Of course they cover other issues as well but mainly traineeships
[normal] and 
[normal]apprenticeships
[normal],
[normal] and another is working on the Youth Guarantee. So we have to distinguish between apprenticeships and traineeships.
[normal]We are fully aware of the differences between member states. There is no one-size-fits-all approach. It simply does not work. In particular, 
[normal]when you look at apprenticeship
[normal] schemes, we have different traditions. You cannot compare countries, like 
[normal]Germany
[normal], 
[normal]Austria
[normal] or 
[normal]Switzerland
[normal]. Their systems have grown over decades if not centuries. Then you have member states—let us take 
[normal]Spain
[normal] or 
[normal]Portugal
[normal]—that want to build up a system. It is a very, very difficult task because there are so many different players: there are the links with educational institutions and you have to get businesses and trade unions on board. We are starting from a very low point in these countries. 
[normal]The European Alliance for Apprenticeships was launched in July. One of its main objectives is, first, to change the mindsets of those member states that do not have apprenticeship schemes yet. That means the mindsets of the companies. If you speak to an Italian company they will tell you, “Why should I have an apprentice? He or she will leave after finishing the apprenticeship and go to my competitor”. When we speak to the trade unions they say, “This is exploitation of young people because they are paid much less”. When we speak to young people
[normal],
[normal] they prefer to go to a construction site and earn three times as much now in the short term, and you speak to the parents and they say, “It is much more prestigious if my daughter and my son go to university”. So there is a big, big mindset problem to start with.
[normal]You also asked about the European role. What we try to do with the European alliance is to bring a lot of pilot projects that are taking place under the European umbrella. There is a lot of interest in many member states 
[normal]in doing 
[normal]something. I have told you that I have been working for a long time in the area of employment and social affairs. I can tell you that usually member states say, “This is not our business. We do a little bit here and there”. This is the one of first times I have seen a real, genuine interest on the part of member states to learn from each other and build up something that works in other member states. Why are apprenticeships so much in vogue these days? It might be a coincidence, but if you look at the map the member states that have well
[normal] 
[normal]established apprenticeship schemes usually have relatively low youth unemployment rates. 
[normal]My personal opinion is 
[normal]that 
[normal]I am a bit sceptical. For me, the apprenticeship scheme is not a panacea. It can help to develop the right skills but it will not solve the dramatic level of youth unemployment. It can be a step. We have all these pieces, like a mosaic, and an apprenticeship is an important part.  But if you speak to some Ministers from some of the countries that want to establish a scheme, they believe that if they establish a system everything will be fine. There is also some scepticism on this side. From our point of view, what is very important is to involve the social partners and the employers when drawing up curricula for the apprenticeships. Successful schemes have that. Only then will young people acquire the skills and the competencies that are needed in the market. It is very important to have a connect between what the market needs, which employers can tell you best, and what the young people will learn.
[normal]This is on the apprenticeship scheme, and while we have some declarations on minimum standards, and some idea of what a good traineeship would look like, we are far from setting standards as we do now in the other area of apprenticeships. In December the Commission adopted a proposal for a European quality framework on traineeships that we are currently negotiating with member states. Like the Youth Guarantee it is in the form of a Council recommendation, so it is not binding but recommending member states to ensure a number of things. There we start with the kind of standard that we would like to see
[normal]. E
[normal]very trainee 
[normal]should have 
[normal]at least a written traineeship agreement setting out a number of issues
[normal]—
[normal]for example, the length of the traineeship. We want to ensure that there are learning objectives during the traineeship. We want to avoid repetitive traineeships because there is a major concern that young people are caught in a number of traineeships even with the same employer. In terms of setting standards, we are further advanced than in the area of apprenticeships because there again the apprenticeship system is much more complicated. In 
[normal]Germany
[normal] the traditions are different. There are many more players involved
[normal]—
[normal]the chambers, employers and educational institutions. That is a broad overview.
[normal]The Chairman:[bold] Thank you very much.
