[normal]Q183 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Lord Wilson of Tillyorn:[bold] [bold]Can
[normal] you clarify the role of the European Social Fund in dealing with youth unemployment and the Youth Guarantee? The memo put out by the Commission in November says, “It is important that member states devote a significant proportion of their European Social Fund allocations for 2014-20 to implementing the Youth Guarantee”. How do you see the ESF fitting in
[normal]?
[normal] 
[normal]C
[normal]an I try to get my mind clear? The suggestions are made by the Council as recommendations. They are not binding. The money is given out by the Commission. That means the Commission is saying, “Okay, this idea is good and we will support it. That idea is not good, we will not support it”. So there is a great deal of power there in the Commission of what—
[normal]Max Uebe:[bold] Ideally, yes, but with shared management you have to agree with a member state. In general, when it comes to the fund, we try to introduce what we call 
[normal]ex ante 
[normal]conditionality. We want to make payments conditional. This is
[normal], in my personal view, in the interest not only 
[normal]of the Commission but also of a number of member states. At least we can control in a certain way where the money goes. When it comes to EU funding of the Youth Guarantee, first, we say the Youth Guarantee needs national funding. EU funding alone will not suffice. Then you have to distinguish between the 
[normal]youth employment initiative—
[normal]the €6 billion package, two years’ short-term Youth Guarantee
[normal]—
[normal]and the ESF, 
[normal]with 
[normal]much larger amounts, 
[normal]for 
[normal]much longer and covering all member states because
[normal]. As 
[normal]you see from th
[normal]is year’s
[normal] money
[normal],
[normal] a number of member states do not benefit at all. So this is an i
[normal]mportant difference between the two.
